[[Image:Kipuka1.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A kīpuka surrounded by lava flows at [[Kīlauea]] [[volcano]], [[Hawai`i]]]]
[[Image:Yakehashiri lava flow Aerial photograph A.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Green kīpukas surrounded by brown lava flows erupted from [[Mount Iwate|Iwate]] volcano, Japan]]

A '''kīpuka''' is an area of land surrounded by one or more younger [[lava]] flows. A kīpuka forms when lava flows on either side of a [[hill]], [[ridge]], or older [[lava dome]] as it moves downslope or spreads from its source. Older and more weathered than their surroundings, kīpukas often appear to be like islands within a sea of lava flows.  They are often covered with [[soil]] and late [[ecological succession]]al [[vegetation]] that provide visual contrast as well as habitat for animals in an otherwise inhospitable environment.{{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}

==Etymology==

''Kīpuka'', along with ''[[aa (lava flow)|{{okina}}a{{okina}}ā]]'' and ''[[pahoehoe|pāhoehoe]]'', are [[Hawaiian language|Hawaiian]] words related to [[volcanology]] that have entered the [[lexicon]] of [[geology]].  Some{{who|date=March 2017}} have used the word informally as applying to any place where biological life endures the encroachment of civilization, an "island of life."{{dubious|date=March 2017}}

==Significance to research==

''Kīpuka'' provides useful study sites for [[Ecology|ecological]] research because they facilitate [[Replication (statistics)|replication]]; multiple ''kīpuka'' in a system (isolated by the same lava flow) will tend to have uniform [[substrate (biology)|substrate]] age and successional characteristics, but are often isolated-enough from their neighbors to provide meaningful, comparable differences in size, [[invasive species|invasion]], etc.  They are also receptive to experimental [[Treatment and control groups|treatments]]. ''Kīpuka'' along [[Saddle Road]] on [[hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i]] have served as the natural laboratory for a variety of studies, examining ecological principles like [[island biogeography]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Flaspohler|first=David J. |author2=Giardina, Asner |author3=Hart, Price |author4=Lyons, Castaneda|title=Long-term effects of fragmentation and fragment properties on bird species richness in Hawaiian forests|journal=Biological Conservation|year=2010|volume=143|pages=280–288|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320709004509|accessdate=3 May 2017|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2009.10.009}}</ref> [[Soil food web#Food web control|food web control]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gruner|first=Daniel S.|title=Attenuation of top-down and bottom-up forces in a complex terrestrial community|journal=Ecology|year=2004|volume=85|pages=3010–3022|url=http://drum.lib.umd.edu/bitstream/1903/7108/1/Gruner2004Ecology.pdf|accessdate=22 August 2013|doi=10.1890/04-0020}}</ref> and [[invader potential|biotic resistance]] to invasiveness.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gruner|first=Daniel S.|title=Biotic resistance to an invasive spider conferred by generalist insectivorous birds on Hawaiʻi Island|journal=Biological Invasions|year=2004|volume=0|pages=1–6|url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/146705q0#page-1|accessdate=22 August 2013|doi=10.1007/s10530-004-2509-2}}</ref>

