'''Paul Shaw''' is an American designer, calligrapher and historian of design who lives in New York.<ref name="Character Studies">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|last2=Coles|first2=Stephen|title=Character Studies|url=http://www.printmag.com/article/stereotype-interview-with-stephen-coles/|website=Print|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Recap of Paul Shaw’s San Francisco Lettering Walk">{{cite web|title=Recap of Paul Shaw’s San Francisco Lettering Walk|url=https://printinghistory.org/shaw-sf-lettering-tour/|website=American Printing History Association|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> He has written a book on the history of the design of the New York subway system, ''Helvetica and the New York Subway System: The True (Maybe) Story'', on the work of [[William Addison Dwiggins]], and for [[Print (magazine)|''Print'' magazine]].<ref name="IDSGN">{{cite web|title=Design discussions: Paul Shaw and the NYC Subway|url=http://idsgn.org/posts/design-discussions-paul-shaw-and-the-nyc-subway/|website=IDSGN|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Heller2013">{{cite book|author=Steven Heller|title=Writing and Research for Graphic Designers: A Designer's Manual to Strategic Communication and Presentation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k42bjx1DOsAC&pg=PA98|date=18 January 2013|publisher=Rockport Publishers|isbn=978-1-59253-804-1|pages=98–9}}</ref><ref name="The (Mostly) True Story of Helvetica and the New York City Subway">{{cite web|last1=Shaw|first1=Paul|title=The (Mostly) True Story of Helvetica and the New York City Subway|url=http://www.aiga.org/the-mostly-true-story-of-helvetica-and-the-new-york-city-subway/|website=AIGA|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="When in Helvetica">{{cite web|last1=Bierut|first1=Michael|authorlink1=Michael Bierut|title=When in Helvetica|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703858404576214492061190946|website=[[Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="How Helvetica Took Over th