{{Infobox Book | name = Science and Religion: Some Historical Perspectives | title_orig = | translator = | image = Science and Religion Some Historical Perspectives.jpg| image_caption = | author = [[John Hedley Brooke]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | pub_date = 1991 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = 0-521-28374-4 | dewey= 291.1/75 20 | congress= BL245 .B77 1991 | oclc= 22451451 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Science and Religion: Some Historical Perspectives''''' is a book on the [[relationship between religion and science]] by [[John Hedley Brooke]].
The book identifies three traditional views of the relationship between science and religion found in historical analyses: conflict, complementarity, and commonality. The book portrays all three as oversimplifications. It offers up the alternative notion of complexity, which bases the relationship between science and religion on changing circumstances where it is defined upon each particular historical situation and the actual beliefs and ideas of the scientific and religious figures involved.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Temperley|first=HNV|title=Science and salvation|journal=Nature|volume=359|pages=685–686|doi=10.1038/359685a0|year=1992|issue=6397}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last = Howell |first = Kenneth J. |coauthors = |year = 1994 |title = Science and Religion Some Historical Perspectives |url = |journal = [[The Journal of Modern History]] |volume = 66 |issue = 4 |pages = 779–782 |doi = 10.1086/244944 |pmid = }}</ref>
==Reception== {{Expand section|what the reviews say about the book|date=August 2009}} [[American Historical Review]] states that the book's bibliographic essay "identifies and … incorporates the results of virtually every significant and relevant article published in the past fifty years."<ref>{{cite journal |last = Olson |first = Richard |coauthors = |year = 1994 |title = Science and Religion Some Historical Perspectives |url = http://jstor.org/stable/2166181 |journal = [[American Historical Review]] |volume = 99 |issue = 1 |pages = 191–192 |doi = 10.2307/2166181 |pmid = |accessdate = 2008-11-12 |publisher = American Historical Association |last2 = Brooke |first2 = John Hedley }}</ref>
